 To find the minimum value of the quadratic $x^2 - 14x + 3$, we need to find the vertex of the parabola. The x-coordinate of the vertex is given by $x = -\frac{b}{2a}$. In this case, $a=1$ and $b=-14$, so the x-coordinate of the vertex is $x = -\frac{-14}{2(1)} = 7$. To make it easier to see what the minimum value will be, we graph the quadratic.
[asy]
Label f;
f.p = fontsize(6);
xaxis(-15,15,Ticks(f, 2.0));
yaxis(-25,25,Ticks(f, 2.0));
real f(real x)
{
return x^2 - 14x + 3;
}
draw(graph(f,-15,-2 -- 8 -- 14,red));
draw((-16,-2)--(16,-2),EndArrow);
draw((-15,23)--(15,23),EndArrow);
label("$x$",(15,23),N);
label("$y$",(16,23),N);
dot((7,f(7)));
dot((-7,f(-7)));
dot((-14,f(-14)));
dot((14,f(14)));
label("$7$",(7,f(7)),N);
label("$-7$",(-7,f(-7)),N);
label("$-14$",(-14,f(-14)),N);
label("$14$",(14,f(14)),N);
[/asy]
